description.plain:
The Lumineers is a band from New Jersey and formed in 2002. The original members consisted of Wesley Schultz and Jeremiah Fraites.

In 2009, the duo moved to Colorado to be able to concentrate on their music. After the addition of Neyla Pekarek on cello and vocals, the band released their first album—written by Schultz and Fraites—in 2012.  Their first single, “Ho Hey,” quickly climbed to Number 1.

In 2016 they released their sophomore album, Cleopatra.

description.plain:
“Ophelia” is “the cornerstone” of The Lumineers’s sophomore album, Cleopatra.  It was the first track written and recorded for the album, following which band member Jeremiah Fraites said he “felt like it was easier to proceed finishing the album.”

The song is also about how the band has dealt with the success it has achieved since it’s 2012 self-titled debut. Singer Wesley Schultz told EW:

”Ophelia“ is a vague reference to people falling in love with fame. That spotlight can seem like an endless buffet, but in reality, you’re just shiny, bright, and new to people for a quick moment—and then you have the rest of your life to live.

description.plain:
Track 5 Of The Lumineers Album.
Ranked at #36 in United States
Wesley Schultz is trying to do the right things the right way, whether it’s in a relationship or in life in general. Although he does say, “it”, which might means he’s trying to do what he’s going through right.

Even though he’s trying to do the right things, his life is lonely. He’s not happy…there is something missing causing him to feel lonliness even though he’s trying to do right, which should bring happiness.

He doesn’t know what he did and when that started the chain of events in action? He doesn’t know why she left him? He doesn’t know how he got so lonely and lost even without her since he’s been trying to do all the right things. Or maybe he thought doing all the right things would bring her back somehow.

He’s not able to tell her these things or they’re not communicating this or she’s not seeing what all he’s doing. A song is a romantic way to tell someone you miss them, or maybe the song is to make himself feel better.

if she would have went to where he was he’d be standing by someone else that wasn’t her, and how would she have felt or what would she have thought? Would that be right? And he’s talking about what it would have been … past tense, was there someone else back then and now he wants her back and she’s moving on and he doesn’t think she’s right for any other guy but him?

The bleeding means life, and seeing his family will bring him back to life, but his life is feeling like it’s fading and he doesn’t want to lose everything he’s been trying to do right while waiting on her. So, obviously, this is a love note in form of a song so he could say it the way he felt it.

description.plain:
The last song on the ‘Gloria’ section of III addresses Gloria’s alcoholism which causes her to struggle with everyday life, especially when it comes to raising her child. The song isn’t necessarily judgemental but is instead a tragic portrayal of someone with a complex addiction.

Wesley Schultz has been open about the inspiration of the song being a family member. Despite changing her name, the story is very personal as he told The Times:

Gloria is real, and she’s close to me. The reason I created characters around her was to give me a buffer to be explicit without exploiting her pain. But it has become my family’s pain, and it was a relief to play them the songs. They feel like I have given them a voice and that it is an honest depiction of an awful situation.

On May 19th 2019, Wesley provided a short description of the song on the band’s Twitter account:

description.plain:
Lead singer Wesley Shultz explained the moment that inspired this song:

This song was [from] the time when my dad had just passed away – so soon after that that the clothes were still in his drawers. And so, I was running late for work and realized I didn’t have black socks. I knew I’d be sent home without those. I was a bartender at a pretty crappy job. I ended up reaching into his sock drawer in a hurry… and unexpectedly pulling out his pistol that I didn’t know he ever had. I was disappointed I couldn’t ask him about it… and what else did I not know about this person that I supposedly so close with.

In the song, Shultz expresses that he’s a different person from who his dad was; for example, he doesn’t own a gun. However, he still has a way to go before he can be a man in his own right, and find a companion.

description.plain:
This is the second song from the ‘Jimmy Sparks’ section of III. It tells the story of a single father with a troubled past who, desperate for money, turns to gambling which alienates him from his son, Junior.

This song takes heavily from the Lumineers earlier track “Nightshade” which was released as part of the Game of Thrones inspired album For The Throne. Entire lines are lifted as well as chord progressions. In an interview with The Times, Schultz makes it clear that they weren’t just recycling the song:

When we were asked for a Game of Thrones song last summer, we’d given up on Jimmy Sparks. After months of fiddling with it, we couldn’t make it work, so we switched the chorus, changed some of the lyrics and gave it away. But in doing that, we suddenly saw where we’d gone wrong. We begged for the song back, but the producers refused. Luckily, they didn’t mind if we also used it. We like to think of it as sampling ourselves, but I admit you could call it recycling.

On their website, the song is described as:

Vivid in its imagery and as devastating in its portrayal of an alienated father and son as a short story by Raymond Carver or David Foster Wallace.

description.plain:
“Patience” is the closing track to Cleopatra and The Lumineers' first instrumental piece.

In an interview, the band’s drummer Jeremiah Frates said the inspiration for “Patience” came from the piano piece “Row” by Jon Brion. Frates also praised “Row” on the band’s “Songs That Inspire Us” Tumblr page, writing, “It’s one minute long. It’s one person and one piano. But it moves me to no end.”

Among other things, the name “Patience” could refer to the four-year wait for The Lumineers' sophomore album release.

“Patience” does not have its own music video; rather, the song is played at the end of the music video for “Angela” off the same album.

The track is written by the perspective of one of the main characters, whose fears and struggles are painted vividly as tough to get over, but at the same time necessary in order to reach the glory he/she has aspired to.

description.plain: This song is about the lead singer, Wesley Schultz’s uncle Charles Schultz who was killed in the war. He was born in 1944 and was the first born of 4 sons, one of which was obviously Wesley’s father. The family lived in Metuchen, NJ. Charles identified with the democrat ideology of the time and was a supporter of JFK, so he believed in Kennedy’s plea to ask what you could do for your country. He felt his country needed him, and in his early twenties he joined the USMC and was deployed to Vietnam. He was killed in action. After the war his home town of Metuchen erected a monument in memory of the three residents who gave their lives in the war.

description.plain: The song tells a story set in the 1920s. Most of us will recognize the time as the “Jazz Age”, when wealth was in abundance and modern American culture began forming. Before then was WW1, which lasted 1912-1918. The leading men of many households had gone off to war, leaving many wives alone to provide for themselves. For a source of income, many women took on paid jobs for the first time. This brought a sense of independence to the ladies of the USA; they realized that they could forge lives for themselves other than that of a humble housewife. When the stock market shot up and money started rolling in, fashion, wild behavior(drinking, smoking, sex), makeup, and other activities that defied earlier social norms were taken up by many young women. These ladies were given the nickname “Flappers”

description.plain:
A cover of leonard Cohen epic poem – “Democracy” where most of the song is annotated extensively.

The first of three bonus tracks from The Lumineers’ album “III”, “Democracy” is a soulful and moving ballad about the current and historical state of the American government and other democracies around the world. Layered with subtle but powerful comments about the pitfalls of societal systems, Democracy takes a similar political theme seen in “Big Parade” from their first album and expands it with their new, but somehow always classic sound.

description.plain:
As the last song from the ‘Junior Sparks’ section of III, “Left for Denver” addresses Junior’s mother, Bonnie, who has left him and his alcoholic father to move away and start again.

Their website provides a short song description:

Junior’s mom moves west and starts a new family in “Left for Denver”; the kid reacts by rebelling and getting in trouble.

The band has a personal connection to Denver as it was after they moved there that they really started to take off. Wesley Schultz expressed his feelings about the city in an interview with The Times:

No one in Denver cares if you’re famous, they care deeply about music — at night this place is packed, whatever the act. There are venues like this all over Denver. But what people here love is to sing along. They don’t go to shows to stand and stare.

description.plain:
“For Fra” was featured on the Target exclusive version of The Lumineers' second LP, ‘Cleopatra’ (2016), before being included on the 2018 ‘C-Sides’.

On Instagram (@thelumineers), Jeremiah Fraites wrote that “For Fra” is “an instrumental piece of music that started off merely as a birthday gift for my then girlfriend – now wife – Francesca. I recorded the piano idea first and then just repeatedly recorded over that with drums, claps, and percussion. While [Wesley Schultz] and I were never able to make this particular idea work into a traditional Lumineers song, it did end up providing us with the basic chords for the song "Angela” much later down the road when we recorded the ‘Cleopatra’ album."

description.plain:
“Visions of China” was released on The Lumineers' 2018 “C-Sides,” after being licensed to the show The Walking Dead for its Season 4 (2013-2014) soundtrack.
On Instagram (@thelumineers), Wesley Schultz wrote of the song: “I lived in Hangzhou, China for 3 months with a good friend who was learning the language. It was because of a language barrier that I often was isolated and left to either be quite bored, or write and record music. The lyrics of this song were a smattering of things I’d seen and sensed there. The song itself had this meditative quality – something about the way the chords rolled in and out without ever feeling tired.”
